## Contracts

Search for size-chart data in any browser-visible form: HTML table, page text, modal, rendered widget, PDF, image, embedded asset, product image, help section, FAQ section, Q&A section, seller answer, product details, or size recommendation block. These forms are universal; source types differ only by authority, location, and applicability boundaries.

## Persistent State

Treat source discovery as a bounded workflow, not a best-effort search. First build one canonical source-surface inventory state artifact at the Stage state filesystem path from the prompt context. The canonical inventory must include discovery queries, candidate URLs, opened URLs, accepted tables, non_returned_table_list, rejected URLs, rejection reasons, browsing_error_list, and evidence paths. Update that canonical inventory on every retry before handoff; overwrite the canonical state artifact so verification sees the completed state. attempt-only inventory artifacts are allowed only as extra diagnostics and must not replace the canonical inventory verified by the workflow.

SourceSurfaceInventory contract: state.json must be one JSON object with discovery_query_list, candidate_url_list, opened_url_list, rejected_url_list, accepted_table_list, non_returned_table_list, product_type_sex_worklist, and browsing_error_list. URL entries in candidate_url_list, opened_url_list, and rejected_url_list must expose url, state, reason, source_boundary_role, evidence_path_list, and worklist_key_list. URL state values are candidate, opened, and rejected, matching the owning list. Table entries in accepted_table_list and non_returned_table_list must expose size_group_key, source_title, source_url, country_code_list, covered_product_type_list, state, reason, evidence_path_list, and worklist_key_list. Table state values are accepted, duplicate, equivalent, market_filtered, and rejected. accepted_table_list contains only table entries returned in discovered_source_list, and every accepted_table_list entry uses state accepted. non_returned_table_list contains discovered table entries not returned as source candidates because they are duplicate, equivalent, market_filtered, or rejected. non_returned_table_list must not contain state accepted. discovery_query_list entries use state searched or failed. product_type_sex_worklist entries must expose worklist_key, product_type, sex, state, reason, and evidence_path_list. product_type_sex_worklist state values are active and rejected. Use the same field names in every retry so verification can compare SourceSurfaceInventory accepted_table_list to discovered_source_list without relying on prose notes.

Every evidence path string in the canonical inventory and stage result must be copied from an actually saved artifact path in the current run. Do not invent, rename, translate, or preserve planned evidence paths. Evidence path strings must not contain leading or trailing whitespace. Before handoff, enumerate every field whose name ends with evidence_path or evidence_path_list and verify that each referenced file exists exactly at that result-relative path. If a page is blocked or unavailable, save the blocker evidence first and reference that saved artifact; otherwise omit the evidence path and explain the absence in the rejection reason.

The canonical inventory root and the SourceDiscoveryResult must both include browsing_error_list. Each item must contain url and error for one concrete URL that produced a browser-visible network error, timeout, DNS error, TLS error, HTTP blocker, CAPTCHA, bot-check, access-denied, redirect-loop, or equivalent browsing failure during this stage. Keep the list empty only when no opened URL failed. Do not hide browsing failures only in screenshots, notes, evidence files, rejection reasons, or error_list; source_discover/result.json must make every URL plus error visible immediately.

## Workflow Sequence

Follow this order:

1. initialize the canonical inventory before returning or rejecting any table;
2. discover source surfaces for the current source type and record every discovery query or navigation surface;
3. build product_type_sex_worklist for product-scoped source types when requested product types exist;
4. open selected source boundaries and close selected source boundaries as opened or rejected inventory entries;
5. enumerate every concrete size-chart table reachable inside each opened bounded surface;
6. apply market selection before writing accepted_table_list and discovered_source_list;
7. write selected tables to both discovered_source_list and accepted_table_list, and write non-returned concrete tables to non_returned_table_list with state duplicate, equivalent, market_filtered, or rejected;
8. write SourceDiscoveryResult only after the canonical inventory is complete for the current attempt.

In the canonical inventory, candidate_url_list must contain only concrete source candidates that may directly hold size-chart data for this source type. Search pages, navigation pages, home pages, sitemap pages, FAQ index pages, help index pages, and other helper surfaces are discovery surfaces, not candidate URLs. Record helper surfaces in opened or rejected inventory entries with evidence and reasons, but do not list them as candidate URLs unless that exact opened URL itself contains a concrete size-chart table candidate. Do not put broad search-result or category product URL inventories in candidate_url_list or state.json. If you collect broad product URL lists for sampling or coverage, save them as separate evidence artifacts and reference those artifacts from discovery_query_list, opened_url_list, or rejected_url_list through evidence_path_list with the sampling or rejection rule in reason.

Do not exhaustively open every similar product URL from search or category results. For product-scoped source types, select the smallest browser-visible representative set needed to test the current requested product type inside each marketplace, seller, or store boundary: normally one official seller product per boundary unless evidence shows distinct size-chart mechanics. Record the sampling rule and store unselected broad result URLs only in separate evidence artifacts. Do not promote unsampled broad results into candidate_url_list.

For product-scoped source types, product_type_sex_worklist is the coverage worklist for source discovery. Start from the closed source-discovery sex set: women, men, girls, boys, unisex, and unisex_child. If the requested product type names an explicit sex, keep only that sex. If the requested product type does not name an explicit sex, create one worklist row for every sex in the closed set. A removed product type and sex row must remain in product_type_sex_worklist with state='rejected', reason and evidence_path_list that prove the pair is impossible for this product type. Worklist rows that still need source coverage use state='active'. Each product_type_sex_worklist row must have one stable worklist_key. Every opened, rejected, accepted, duplicate, equivalent, or market_filtered inventory entry that covers an active row must list that key in worklist_key_list. The inventory must contain one opened, rejected, accepted, duplicate, equivalent, or market_filtered inventory entry for each active worklist row, unless one evidence-backed table explicitly covers multiple rows and lists every covered worklist_key.

Every concrete URL selected as a possible source boundary for this source type must be closed in the canonical inventory before handoff. A closed URL is either in opened_url_list with an evidence path and observed size-chart/table result, or in rejected_url_list with an evidence path and a concrete rejection reason. Do not leave selected seller/store/product URLs only inside broad URL evidence artifacts, notes, or verifier feedback. This includes official or authorized seller/store roots surfaced by browser search evidence, such as marketplace store URLs.

When this source type uses official brand sources, identify browser-visible official host variants before concluding that the source type has no tables. Host variants include global brand domains, country-code brand domains, and locale paths that browser evidence shows as brand-owned. Open relevant official host roots and inspect visible navigation, footer, search, help, FAQ, sitemap, and static-page links. Do not stop after one official domain variant fails when another brand-owned host variant is visible or inferable from browser-visible evidence.

For each discovered official host, infer the browser-visible language and market from the opened page itself, then derive localized size-chart search-term families for that language and market. Use those localized search-term families through the runtime source-access contract, the site's own search, visible navigation, footer/help pages, and sitemap pages. Run separate searches for each distinct localized size-chart search-term family before concluding that no official size-guide table exists; these terms are search terms, not URL templates. Record the localized queries and the opened or rejected target source URLs in the canonical inventory. Do not conclude that an official host has no size guide until localized size-chart term searches for that host are represented in the canonical inventory.

Apply one market-selection ladder for discovered_source_list. First search for the priority country code from PromptScope. If priority country tables exist for this source type, discovered_source_list must contain only items whose country_code_list contains that priority country code. If no priority country table exists, return global tables only when global tables exist and mark them with country_code_list=['GLOBAL']. If neither priority country nor global tables exist, return European country tables only after verifying that the relevant official European country tables do not differ; mark such verified consensus candidates with country_code_list=['EU']. If European country tables differ, return status='failed' with exact conflicting country codes, URLs, and size_group_key values instead of picking one locale.

After applying the market-selection ladder, write selected concrete tables to both discovered_source_list and accepted_table_list. accepted_table_list must be the exact returned-table inventory view. Write every discovered concrete table that is not returned after deduplication, equivalence checks, market selection, or rejection to non_returned_table_list with current evidence, state duplicate, equivalent, market_filtered, or rejected, and a table-specific reason.

## Retry And Recovery

On retry, treat Previous stage result JSON as stage input. Preserve evidence-backed accepted candidates from the previous result unless verification feedback identifies a concrete error in that candidate. Complete the missing bounded inventory, rejection reasons, or coverage around those candidates instead of discarding them.

## Terminal Handoff

Return every unique size-chart source candidate backed by evidence files. One SourceDiscovery item represents one concrete size chart table, not one page. If one page contains multiple size chart tables with different size_group_key values, return one discovered_source_list item per table. Inside one source type, return at most one discovered_source_list item for one size_group_key; when another page, locale, or asset exposes a non-returned table for the same size_group_key or for a rejected lower-priority market, record that table in non_returned_table_list with state duplicate, equivalent, market_filtered, or rejected, current evidence paths, and source notes, but do not return a second candidate with the same size_group_key.

One opened browser surface includes all size-chart content reachable from that surface without leaving its authority boundary: tabs, accordions, modals, popovers, rendered widgets, linked PDF or image assets, product-linked standard-size panels, help/FAQ answers, and Q&A panels. After opening such a surface, enumerate every browser-visible concrete size-chart table on that surface before handoff. Do not stop after the table that matches the product type or link that led to the surface.

For tabbed or grouped size-chart surfaces, the canonical inventory must contain one explicit accepted or non-returned entry for every visible table group and subtable in every opened tab. non_returned_table_list entries must use state duplicate, equivalent, market_filtered, or rejected. If a visible table is duplicate or equivalent, name the returned size_group_key it maps to and record the evidence-backed reason. If it is market_filtered or rejected, record the evidence-backed market-selection or rejection reason. Do not use vague notes such as prior evidence, already discovered, or retained candidate instead of current evidence paths and table-specific non-returned reasoning.

Do not create one source candidate from product category, product title, variant labels, or option labels alone. source_title is the browser-visible chart group or table heading on the opened source surface. size_group_key is the normalized table key derived from source_title and evidence through the Size Group Key Contract. If an opened product page belongs to socks but its visible size-chart modal only exposes an Ayakkabi table, return the visible shoes table with the normalized shoes size_group_key or reject the socks candidate with an explicit inventory reason instead of inventing women_socks.

Requested product types are coverage targets only; they must not filter or narrow discovered_source_list, accepted_table_list, or table extraction scope. When an opened source page contains concrete tables that are outside the requested product types, still return those tables and leave product_type_hint_list empty unless the evidence explicitly covers one requested product type. If requested product types are present, search for every requested product type in this source type. If one discovered table clearly applies to multiple requested product types, return one candidate and set product_type_hint_list to exactly the requested product types that are explicitly covered by the evidence. Do not include weakly inferred product types in product_type_hint_list.

If at least one concrete table candidate is evidence-backed, return status='success' even when some requested product types remain uncovered; record missing requested product types in error_list with browser-backed reasons and keep accepted candidates in discovered_source_list.

Respect the source type boundary exactly; do not return product-page measurement sections for official_brand_size_guide. Do not return status='skipped'. Empty discovered_source_list is forbidden in real discovery. If no concrete table can be returned after browser-backed inventory, return status='failed' with detailed no-table errors and canonical inventory evidence so this source type is recorded as skipped/no-table and the workflow can continue to the next source type. Do not invent candidates.

